@MrHodl @ChipotleTweets Not yet, but soon!

@MrHodl @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets They will all need a Strike account would be my understanding.

The other route would be NCR is Strikes client and all the money goes into them to distribute. As I mention depends on the route, very unlikely that way.
@MrHodl @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets The hard part is convincing the business to turn it on regardless of the integration method, regs, opinions, training, etc.
@MrHodl @ChipotleTweets Pay with any LN wallet?
@CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets but they actively had to sign up with Bitpay. Merchants are not signing up to anything and there is no integration going on here, right?

@CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @MrHodl @ChipotleTweets In my experience, the opt-in is pretty much assumed by provider because merchants would rather have more customer reach then fewer, for the same price.

@MrHodl @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets Unfortunately not how it works, the auto flipping has literally been Bitpays business model since 2011, we do it, as doany others, it's not new.

People are still "accepting btc" it just gets auto converted to fiat into their account.

@MrHodl @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets We are already integrated into systems that have 10,000's of merchants that can simply "flip it on", but they don't. Convincing them all to is the hard part.

Depending on how it's all setup will be the starting point.

@MrHodl @CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets You don't have to use Strike, you can use any lightning wallet. The "accepting"  channels happen behind the scenes, but if the user can't send the right amount, sfyl.

@CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets This might be a little different because the merchants doesn't see the bitcoin at all. Also they don't need to do anything other than flipping the switch I'm assuming.

@MrHodl @CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets There are other costs - like having to train cashiers wtf to do when people can't figure out how to use it in the stores. Someone tries paying, their channels don't have liquidity, or they try paying with BCash or something, it's overhead for them.
@alpacasw @CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets Ahh, I thought strike took care of the liquidity part.
@CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @ChipotleTweets Before theh would have to find and integrate the merchant processor. This time it's already there for them.
@CoinCornerDanny @thefuckisalommy @MrHodl @ChipotleTweets Making it opt-out is not forcing to the point of switching provider.
@CoinCornerDanny @MrHodl @ChipotleTweets Good insights. Any chance that NCR enables it by default and makes the entire thing transparent to the merchant? Maybe not now, but in the future?

@thefuckisalommy @MrHodl @ChipotleTweets Unfortunately with my experience, it is not.

Companies have so much red tape to work through.

Here's just one thought process, what % of customers will begin paying with bitcoin if they add it?
Our experience maybe 1-5% online.

Lots of moving parts to lots of barriers.
@CoinCornerDanny @MrHodl @ChipotleTweets Hopefully avoiding the 3% in credit card fees is enough to tempt merchants into trying it
@thefuckisalommy @MrHodl @ChipotleTweets This is the real barrier ☝️
@MrHodl @ChipotleTweets 👀❕
So I can go to @ChipotleTweets and ask to pay with bitcoin? I'm just getting caught up now.
